<Docs title="Manifest Format" description="The normative grammar of a .life manifest head — the strict subset, the frozen waist, and the addressed-section construct of format epoch 2 (life: 1.0).">
  <h1>Manifest format</h1>
  <p class="lead">The normative grammar of a <code>.life</code> manifest head — format <strong>epoch&nbsp;2</strong> (<code>life: 1.0</code>). The reference implementation is the engine's own parser (<code>kernel/lib/grammar.js</code> + <code>kernel/lib/parser.js</code>, shipped as the <a href="/registry?q=life">life</a> engine); conformance is defined by the fixture set below, not by what any YAML library tolerates. Key words <strong>MUST</strong>, <strong>SHOULD</strong>, and <strong>MAY</strong> are used as in RFC&nbsp;2119.</p>

  <h2>Shape of a <code>.life</code> file</h2>
  <p>A <code>.life</code> file is a <strong>head</strong> and a <strong>body</strong>, separated by the first line that is exactly <code>---</code>. The head is the machine surface this document specifies. The body is free-form Markdown — the cell's README, read first by any human or agent that lands there — and this spec places <strong>no</strong> constraint on it. A file with no <code>---</code> separator is all head.</p>

  <h2>Why the grammar is ours, not YAML's</h2>
  <p>A full YAML parser accepts a vast surface — anchors, tags, flow style, block scalars, implicit typing — and disagrees with itself across implementations. Each of those is a way for a manifest to parse into something other than what its author sees, and a head that silently mis-parses can drop a cell's hooks, skills, and provides out of the graph without a word (the incident that motivated the epoch: an unquoted <code>summary:</code> containing <code>: </code> once removed the constitution from every session). Epoch&nbsp;2 replaces the library with a <strong>strict subset</strong> the engine owns end to end, so that <em>the only way a head parses is the way it reads</em>, and anything outside the subset is a <strong>fatal error with line, column, and the fix</strong> — never a silent reinterpretation.</p>

  <h2>The head grammar</h2>
  <p>The head is a sequence of top-level <code>key: value</code> entries. A conforming parser MUST accept exactly the following and reject everything else.</p>
  <dl>
    <dt>Encoding</dt>
    <dd>UTF-8. Indentation is spaces only — a <strong>tab</strong> character in indentation is a fatal error (<code>tab character</code>).</dd>
    <dt>Keys</dt>
    <dd>A top-level key matches <code>[a-z][a-z0-9_-]*</code>. A nested key matches <code>[A-Za-z_][A-Za-z0-9_.-]*</code> — dotted and mixed-case keys are real (environment-variable names, dotted config like <code>service.ARTIFACT</code>). A <strong>duplicate key</strong> at the same level is a fatal error (<code>duplicate key 'name'</code>).</dd>
    <dt>Scalars</dt>
    <dd>A scalar is a single-quoted string, a double-quoted string, or a plain string. <code>true</code>/<code>false</code> and <strong>integer</strong> literals are the <em>only</em> non-string types — there is no float, null, date, or other implicit type. A plain scalar that contains <code>:</code> is a fatal error (<code>plain scalar contains ':'</code>) with the fix to quote it: this is what makes <code>life: 1.0</code> the <em>string</em> <code>"1.0"</code> (decimals stay strings) and closes the Norway problem (<code>no</code>, <code>on</code>, <code>1.0</code> never coerce). Quote any scalar that carries a <code>:</code> or <code>#</code>.</dd>
    <dt>Block lists</dt>
    <dd>A key whose value is a list takes indented <code>- item</code> lines. Each item is a scalar or a one-line flat map. A map item written unquoted in a scalar list (<code>- cap: mode</code>) is the old flatten ambiguity and is rejected — quote it (<code>- "cap: mode"</code>).</dd>
    <dt>Block maps</dt>
    <dd>A key whose value is a map takes an indented block of nested <code>key: value</code> entries. Nesting is bounded at <strong>5 container levels beneath any top-level key</strong> (<code>nesting deeper than 5 levels</code>); a deeper structure MUST be flattened.</dd>
    <dt>Comments</dt>
    <dd><code>#</code> begins a comment to end of line. Comments are preserved by the migration codemod but carry no semantics.</dd>
    <dt>Forbidden</dt>
    <dd>Flow style (<code>&#123;…&#125;</code>/<code>[…]</code>), anchors/aliases/tags/directives (<code>&amp; * ! % @ `</code>), block scalars (<code>|</code>/<code>&gt;</code>), multi-document streams, and any implicit typing beyond the above are each a fatal error naming the offending construct and the fix.</dd>
  </dl>
  <p>Every rejection carries <code>file:line:col</code> and a one-line <code>fix:</code>. A head that does not parse does not silently degrade — its cell's contributions go inactive and the engine says so loudly.</p>

  <h2>The waist — the pre-gene bootstrap closure</h2>
  <p>The head's reserved keys are the <strong>waist</strong>: exactly what the engine must understand <em>before any gene is loaded</em> — identity, the dependency graph, and the session-contribution family it compiles from. The waist is closed; a conforming engine reads these keys directly, and everything else is an addressed section (below). Every waist key is optional except <code>life</code>.</p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>key</th><th>what it is</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>life</code></td><td>epoch marker. <code>1.0</code> selects this grammar; any other value (or its absence) is a fatal error naming the migration codemod.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>name</code></td><td>the cell/gene identity — pool slug and resource-name prefix.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>summary</code></td><td>the one-line description — the manifest's human-facing scalar, and the <em>only</em> descriptive field in the waist (the engine's own boot census / <code>status</code> / <code>ask</code> print it). Everything else a cell is <em>about</em> — icon, tags, and the publish fields — lives in the <code>meta:</code> section (below).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>imports</code></td><td>exact-pinnable dependencies (a pool gene or a local node).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>requires</code></td><td>capabilities this cell composes against — <strong>gene-satisfiable only</strong> (see composition, below).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>provides</code></td><td>capabilities this cell offers to the graph.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>hooks</code></td><td>contributed lifecycle behaviour. Per-hook <code>priority</code> lives inside the spec.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>commands</code></td><td>contributed verbs. A <code>run:</code> MUST be <code>node &lt;file&gt;.js</code> — the dual-harness rule (below).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>skills</code></td><td>contributed skill directories (slash commands are skills).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>mcp</code></td><td>contributed MCP servers — portable across harnesses.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>path</code></td><td>contributed PATH directories (container harnesses; ignored by the shell-less isolate).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>tests</code> / <code>checks</code></td><td>the quality gates the engine itself runs — the publish gate and environment assertions.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>local</code></td><td>consumer-owned paths the vendor step MUST never clobber.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>inputs</code></td><td>values the install flow gathers before a gene is materialized — the definitional pre-gene read.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>shape</code></td><td>structural intent (<code>flat</code> marks an intentional accumulator) — read by the engine's own census.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>publishes</code></td><td>the pool gene this cell is the source of — read by the publish-drift probe.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>allow_local_imports</code></td><td>pre-publish exceptions to the register-first gate — an engine security rail.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Addressed sections</h2>
  <p>Every <strong>non-waist</strong> top-level key MUST be the <strong>address of a consumer</strong>: either the <code>name</code> of a gene reachable from this cell (imported, or in the baseline genome), or a <strong>capability role with a resolved provider</strong> — <code>infra:</code> routes to whatever gene provides the infra adapter, <code>github:</code> to the repo adapter, and so on. The section's content is <strong>opaque to the engine</strong>: it is passed through whole to its addressee, whose schema that gene alone owns and documents. This is the pyproject <code>[tool.*]</code> construct made first-class — the head is the waist plus letters to your genes.</p>
  <p>An <strong>unaddressed</strong> top-level key is a hard error, not a warning. A cell carrying one <strong>deactivates</strong> — its own hooks, skills, and provides go inactive and <code>test</code> reds — but it is never removed from the graph: its <code>name</code> still addresses sibling sections and its <code>imports</code> still install, so a cold materialize can always install the very gene that would address it. One role is always addressable without any gene reachable to address it: <code>meta:</code> — the descriptive-metadata section (<code>icon</code>, <code>tags</code>, <code>description</code>, <code>author</code>, <code>license</code>, <code>homepage</code>, <code>repository</code>, <code>keywords</code>): what a cell is <em>about</em>, read by the viewer chrome and the registry catalog, and by the engine's own publish path, but never by the engine's composition. Descriptive metadata is substrate, not a peer gene, so a head carrying its own <code>meta:</code> never deactivates for want of vendoring an owning gene.</p>
  <p>Adapter section schemas are documented by their owning genes, not here: see the <a href="/docs/adapters/infrastructure">infrastructure</a>, <a href="/docs/adapters/harness">harness</a>, and <a href="/docs/adapters/storage">repo</a> adapter references.</p>

  <h2>Composition is not provisioning</h2>
  <p><code>requires:</code>/<code>provides:</code> mean <strong>gene composition only</strong> — "another gene in the graph satisfies this." They never name an infrastructure primitive. A cell's infra needs are declared in the <code>infra:</code> addressed section as <code>needs: [compute, kv, datastore, …]</code> (bare capability names) and realized by the infra adapter, which never reads <code>requires:</code>. The two are different speech acts: composition wires genes to each other; provisioning asks a provider to stand a resource up. The infra need vocabulary is owned by the adapter contract and is deliberately <strong>not</strong> frozen into this spec until a second adapter proves it from outside — a waist is extracted from running implementations, never legislated.</p>

  <h2>The dual-harness rule</h2>
  <p>A <code>.life</code> is harness-agnostic: it compiles onto a container harness (Claude Code, Codex) and a shell-less Worker isolate alike. A <code>commands</code> or <code>hooks</code> <code>run:</code> that is not <code>node &lt;file&gt;.js</code> silently no-ops in the isolate, so it is a <strong>fatal parse error</strong>, not a lint. (<code>pre_tool</code> hooks, which guard a Bash tool the isolate does not have, are the one documented exception.) A bare <code>true</code>/<code>false</code> item in <code>tests:</code>/<code>checks:</code> is likewise fatal — it would type as a boolean and be skipped silently, a lying-green.</p>

  <h2>Epoch and migration</h2>
  <p>The engine parses <code>life: 1.0</code> heads only. There is <strong>no</strong> dual-read and no auto-migrate shim — a <code>life: 0.1</code> head (or a markerless one) is a hard error naming the one-shot verb <code>life codemod</code>, which rewrites a whole tree's heads to epoch 2 in place (comments preserved, each output verified against this grammar before anything is written). Old pinned versions stay resolvable as archival bytes for old engines — total versioning means the flip strands nothing. From this epoch forward every registry publish is signed and the registry <strong>requires</strong> provenance (see the <a href="/docs/spec/registry-protocol">registry protocol</a>); the optional-signing phase never existed.</p>

  <h2>Conformance</h2>
  <p>An implementation conforms iff it produces the specified outcome for every fixture below. These are drawn verbatim from the engine's executable conformance rail (<code>kernel/tests/epoch-grammar.test.mjs</code>), which is the machine oracle; this table is its human face.</p>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>head fixture</th><th>required outcome</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>life: 1.0</code> + valid waist + an addressed section whose gene is reachable</td><td><strong>accept</strong>; the section rides the index opaque</td></tr>
      <tr><td>a <code>life: 0.1</code> head</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>pre-epoch head ('life: 0.1')</code>, names <code>life codemod</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>no <code>life:</code> marker</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>no 'life:' marker</code>, names <code>life codemod</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>an unaddressed top-level key <code>frobnicate:</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — names the key and the reachable-gene-or-role rule; the cell deactivates but is not dropped</td></tr>
      <tr><td>a plain <code>summary:</code> value containing <code>: </code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> at <code>line:col</code> — <code>plain scalar contains ':'</code> + quote fix</td></tr>
      <tr><td>flow style <code>requires: [a, b]</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>flow style is outside the epoch-2 subset</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>an anchor <code>name: &amp;x broken</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>'&amp;' opens a YAML feature</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>a block scalar <code>summary: |</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>block scalars are outside the subset</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>tab-indented line</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>tab character</code> at <code>line:1</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>a duplicate <code>name:</code> key</td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>duplicate key 'name'</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>a command <code>run:</code> that is not <code>node …</code></td><td><strong>reject</strong> — <code>dual-harness law</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>a <code>pre_tool</code> hook with a non-node <code>run:</code></td><td><strong>accept</strong> — the documented exception</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>A clean-room second implementation of the engine parser is expected to be validated against this set; it is the on-ramp, independent of the reference code.</p>
</Docs>
